Make The Call!\nHomeowners often make risky assumptions about whether or not they should get their utility lines marked, but every digging job requires a call to 811 \u2013 even small projects like planting trees and shrubs. The depth of utility lines varies and there may be multiple utility lines in a common area. Digging without calling can disrupt service to an entire neighborhood, harm you and those around you and potentially result in fines and repair costs. Calling 811 before every digging job gets your underground utility lines marked for free and helps prevent undesired consequences.\nWhile trees clean our air, provide shade and beauty, and make our yards and homes more comfortable, planting them is complicated and must be thoughtfully planned out. When planting your tree, you may be tempted to plant where the tree would look the best or provide the most shade, but that could be a mistake. Not only could you damage an underground utility line when you plant it, but as your tree matures its roots may grow into your utility lines and disrupt your service, requiring you to remove what you've planted. Or, a tree planted too close to your home could damage your foundation. Think above you too...make sure your new tree will not grow tall enough to interfere with overhead lines either. \nTexas law requires homeowners digging at least 16\u201d or more in depth to call 811 at least 48 hours in advance to get their utility lines marked. By calling 811 a few days before you dig, you'll make sure your tree will provide all the benefits you want while still protecting your property and family.\nRemember, know what's below and always make the free call to 811 before you dig. It\u2019s the law in Texas!\nFor more information, visit www.texas811.org", "id": "435209283199980_4507230", "user_likes": false}]}, "actions": [{"link": "https://www.facebook.com/283145907175/posts/435209283199980", "name": "Comment"}, {"link": "https://www.facebook.com/283145907175/posts/435209283199980", "name": "Like"}], "updated_time": "2012-12-03T17:16:52+0000", "caption": "texasforestservice.tamu.edu", "link": "http://bit.ly/VaH6AY", "shares": {"count": 6}, "created_time": "2012-11-30T17:17:19+0000", "message": "Hundreds of Southeast Texas families still recovering from the devastating effects of last year\u2019s drought and wildfires will receive a tangible symbol of hope next week as 500 free trees are distributed through Texas ReLeaf. http://bit.ly/VaH6AY", "icon": "https://fbstatic-a.akamaihd.net/rsrc.php/v2/yD/r/aS8ecmYRys0.gif", "type": "link", "id": "283145907175_435209283199980", "status_type": "shared_story", "description": "Nov. 30, 2012 \u2014 CONROE, Texas \u2014 Hundreds of Southeast Texas families still recovering from the devastating effects of last year\u2019s drought and wildfires will receive a tangible symbol of hope next week as 500 free trees are distributed through Texas ReLeaf.Funded by a partnership between Texas A&M Fo..."}

The first smoke jump in Texas was, also,  in 1946, when  five Gila  NF (NM)  smokejumpers deployed into the Sublett Fire in Big Bend National Park.  Not only was this the first jump in Texas, but it was a record for the first southern-most fire jump. States can have operational control of SEATs, unlike heavies, through an 'exclusive use contract' which is a shirt term contract between a state agent and a contractor for exclusive aircraft to be used by them on thier fires only. The heavies are national assets and can be moved by the region as needed, just cause 910 is in Austin now, and we are burning, doesn't mean he can leave tonight to go some where else.", "id": "10150412832327176_20746440", "user_likes": false}, {"from": {"id": "100002635830689", "name": "Gina Isenberg-Pace"}, "like_count": 0, "can_remove": false, "created_time": "2011-10-06T02:11:50+0000", "message": "California has had an exclusive use contract every year during fire season until this year, when their budget was cut.
